二、指定教科書及參考資料 Textbooks and Reference(請修課同學遵守智慧財產權，不得非法影印)


●指定教科書 Required TextsThe following works can be found in X. J. Kennedy’s An Introduction To Fiction:Shirley Jackson, “The Lottery”James Joyce, “Araby”Ambrose Bierce, “An Occurrence at Owl Creek Bridge”
		●參考書資料暨網路資源 Reference Books and Online ResourcesThe following works, among others, will be frequently mentioned in class; they are so interesting that you simply cannot resist the temptation of reading them; copies are available in school library.N. Howthorne, The Scarlet LetterJane Austen, Pride and PrejudiceM. Proust, Remembrance of Things PastJ. Fowles, The French Lieutenant’s WomanA. Walker, The Color PurpleD. Barthelme, “The Glass Mountain”


三、教學目標 Objectives


The course aims to explore some of the most accomplished Anglo-American writers of short fiction and the novel. It also introduces the student to various genres of English Fiction. We shall start with a collection of short stories by such authors as Jackson, James, Joyce, Cather, Fitzgerald, Faulkner, Malamaud, Oates, Barthelme,  etc., and read them chronologically to get an over-view of this long stretch of literary history and sense of the distinctive periods within it, then we will explore works (including but not limited to) such as Pride and Prejudice, Robinson Crusoe, The Great Expectations, The Scarlet Letter, Heart of Darkness, Daisy Miller, Lady Chatterley’s Lover, Lolita, The Brave New World, The French Lieutenant’s Woman. Through the reading, the historical and thematic evolutions of the Western novel will be traced, analyzed, and explored. By the end of the course you will hopefully have gained some thematic understanding of what “the world of fiction” is about, and you should also have begun to develop an appreciation of literature and the ability to interpret it orally and in writing.　


四、課程內容 Course Description


●整體敘述 Overall DescriptionThis class will be taught in an “open-ended” way, with relatively short lectures from me, and lots of discussions with you. For this matter, your active attendance and participation in class are expected. Bring your opinions to class, and be prepared to argue vigorously, listen, and enjoy.

